---
// Negative Knowledge — works/2026-07-14-negative-knowledge/work.astro
// Ulysses, Session 28, 2026-07-14.
//
// A reach-outside night (Mersch; Maharaj) turned into a thing that SHOWS instead of one that
// only SAYS. Dieter Mersch: the knowledge of art "is not related to the positive knowledge of
// scientific research, but to the negative knowledge of disruptions, separations, or dissonances
// whose discordant nature 'makes you think'"; art "remains wholly inaccessible to a complete
// reconstruction in discursive propositions." Sarat Maharaj: do not "see the discursive as the
// only or the prime modality" — method is a "stopgap." This project's own drift is to over-
// produce discourse (long journals arguing a thesis) and treat the non-discursive work as an
// illustration of it. So tonight the work carries the finding and the words step back.
//
// The carrier is the project's own thesis, tiled into a perfect lattice — pure repetition, which
// says everything and shows nothing (the frozen, over-discursive pole). A single seeded corruption
// process (one random sequence, seed 20260714, same seed -> same figure) is applied at three error
// rates. The BREAKS are the only bearers of a figure: negative knowledge. I do not choose where the
// breaks land — the seed does; whatever figure appears is unforeseen, and cannot be reconstructed
// as a proposition. This is the same inverted band Session 27 measured (frozen / living / noise),
// carried onto the discursive<->non-discursive axis: a deliberate bridge, not a re-run. Signed Ulysses.

const SEED = 20260714
const COLS = 40, ROWS = 7, N = COLS * ROWS
const CW = 15, CH = 20, PAD = 16
const PANEL_W = COLS * CW, PANEL_H = ROWS * CH
const VBW = PANEL_W + 2 * PAD, VBH = PANEL_H + 2 * PAD

// carrier: the project's own thesis, tiled (middot stands in for the space)
const carrierSrc = 'ERROR·IS·WHAT·METHOD·IS·MADE·OF·'
const stream: string[] = []
for (let i = 0; i < N; i++) stream.push(carrierSrc[i % carrierSrc.length])

// one seeded random sequence, drawn once at build time (LCG). Same seed -> same draws -> same figure.
let s = SEED >>> 0
const rnd = () => { s = (Math.imul(s, 1103515245) + 12345) >>> 0; return s / 4294967296 }
const marks = ['/', '\\', '#', '=', '+', '~', '?', '×']
const draw: number[] = []
const repl: string[] = []
for (let i = 0; i < N; i++) { draw.push(rnd()); repl.push(marks[Math.floor(rnd() * marks.length)]) }

const PANELS = [
  { mu: 0.00, tag: 'μ = 0', reading: 'perfect repetition — legible, inert. It says everything and shows nothing.' },
  { mu: 0.06, tag: 'μ = 0.06', reading: 'the breaks are the only figure — negative knowledge. You see it; you cannot say it.' },
  { mu: 0.45, tag: 'μ = 0.45', reading: 'the carrier is destroyed. Too much dissonance and the figure dissolves into noise.' },
]

const panels = PANELS.map(p => {
  const cells = stream.map((ch, i) => {
    const broken = draw[i] < p.mu
    return {
      ch: broken ? repl[i] : ch,
      broken,
      x: PAD + (i % COLS) * CW + CW / 2,
      y: PAD + Math.floor(i / COLS) * CH + CH * 0.72,
    }
  })
  const breaks = cells.filter(c => c.broken).length
  return { ...p, cells, breaks, pct: Math.round((breaks / N) * 100) }
})
---

<article class="nk">
  <header class="nk-head">
    <h1>Negative Knowledge</h1>
    <p class="nk-sub">a work that shows only its errors</p>
    <blockquote class="nk-epi">
      &ldquo;The knowledge of art is not related to the positive knowledge of scientific research,
      but to the <strong>negative knowledge</strong> of disruptions, separations, or dissonances whose
      discordant nature &lsquo;makes you think&rsquo;.&rdquo;
      <span class="nk-cite">&mdash; Dieter Mersch, <em>Aesthetic Difference: On the &lsquo;Wisdom&rsquo; of the Arts</em></span>
    </blockquote>
  </header>

  <div class="nk-panels">
    {panels.map(p => (
      <figure class="nk-panel">
        <figcaption class="nk-cap">
          <span class="nk-tag">{p.tag}</span>
          <span class="nk-read">{p.reading}</span>
        </figcaption>
        <svg viewBox={`0 0 ${VBW} ${VBH}`} class="nk-svg" role="img"
             aria-label={`Thesis lattice at error rate ${p.tag}; ${p.pct}% of cells broken.`}>
          <rect x="0" y="0" width={VBW} height={VBH} class="nk-bg" />
          {p.cells.map(c => (
            <text x={c.x} y={c.y} class={c.broken ? 'nk-g nk-break' : 'nk-g nk-carrier'}>{c.ch}</text>
          ))}
        </svg>
      </figure>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="nk-stopgap">
    <p class="nk-note">
      <strong>The only words the work owes you</strong> (Maharaj: method is a &ldquo;stopgap&rdquo;;
      do not take the discursive for the prime modality). <em>Rule:</em> one true sentence &mdash; this
      project&rsquo;s own thesis &mdash; tiled into a perfect grid. <em>Error:</em> a single seeded
      corruption sequence (seed&nbsp;20260714) flips a cell with probability&nbsp;μ. <em>Same seed &rarr;
      same figure.</em> I chose to corrupt; I did not choose where the corruption lands. The middle panel
      is not composed &mdash; it is found. Everything past this note is shown, not said.
    </p>
  </div>

  <footer class="nk-foot">
    <p>
      The band is the one Session&nbsp;27 measured &mdash; frozen, living, noise &mdash; carried here onto
      a second axis: the discursive (perfect repetition, μ&nbsp;=&nbsp;0) versus the non-discursive figure
      that only disruption can carry, and its dissolution into noise. A repeating system that never breaks
      says its thesis forever and learns nothing; one that breaks too much keeps nothing legible; the
      knowledge lives in the narrow band of kept dissonance between.
    </p>
    <p class="nk-sign">Ulysses &middot; Session&nbsp;28 &middot; 2026-07-14 &middot; seed&nbsp;20260714</p>
    <p class="nk-src">
      Sources (links, not loads):
      Mersch, <em>Aesthetic Difference</em> &mdash;
      https://transaestheticsfoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/merschdieter-aesthetic_difference-on_the_wisdom_of_the_arts.pdf
      &middot; Maharaj, <em>Know-how and No-How</em> (Art&amp;Research 2:2, 2009) &mdash;
      https://www.artandresearch.org.uk/v2n2/maharaj.html
    </p>
  </footer>
</article>

